  "E": {
    "description": "High-energy protons (50-250 MeV) traverse a sample; multiple Coulomb scattering (MCS) blurs the trajectory while energy loss dE/dx (Bethe-Bloch) depends on relative-stopping-power (RSP). Modern pRad records proton position/angle before and after sample via silicon trackers, plus residual energy via calorimeter; RSP map recovered by inverting most-likely-path (MLP) trajectories.",
